title: Area Roundup: Garder-South Wilmington wins senior night volleyball game
text:
Area Roundup: Garder-South Wilmington wins senior night volleyball game Published: Wednesday, Oct. 14, 2015 10:47 p.m. CDT By: STAFF REPORTS 
GARDNER – Senior night was a success for the Gardner-South Wilmington volleyball team Tuesday as the Panthers defeated River Valley Conference rival Donovan, 26-25, 25-15. Related Links 
Leading the Panthers (15-5, 7-3) was Marlana Ferrari with eight kills, two blocks and two aces, while Lexi Robison added seven kills and two aces. 
Celia Barna distributed 11 assists and Sydney Perkins had nine. 
G-SW also won the JV match, 25-13, 25-18, behind five kills and three aces from Mady Asbridge and four kills and five aces by Kaylee Steichen. Emily Monbarren had three blocks and Delaney Miller had five assists, while Mariah Anderson and Cadee Grieff had six and five digs, respectively. 
Herscher 25-25, Seneca 17-20: Emily Woods had three kills, five assists and four blocks for Seneca (12-15, 1-7) in an Interstate Eight loss. Michaela Coughlin had three kills, while Cora Wilkinson had two kills and two aces. 
Mackenzie Maierhofer led with 10 digs, while Karlie Cade had seven assists and five digs. Rachel Alley added five blocks. Seneca won the JV match, 17-25, 25-22, 26-24, to improve to 16-3 overall and 8-0 in the I-8. Brittney Harms led with six kills and 13 digs. 
FOOTBALL 
Morris sophomores 34, Kaneland 14: Kaneland got on the board first Friday night, but Morris came back with 34 unanswered points. Denver Vandover scored with a 9-yard touchdown run. 
After Kaden Laurie intercepted a pass for Morris in the second quarter, the Redskins (4-3) drove the ball down the field, and Mitch Mayberry finished the drive with a quarterback sneak for a touchdown. Morris continued its scoring in the second half with a Tyler Petty 1-yard touchdown run, before Kam Dransfeldt and Kyle Olson each had 5-yard touchdown runs. 
BOYS SOCCER 
Yorkville 9, Morris 1: Senior night at Yorkville proved to be a tough game for Morris. The Redskins (6-13, 0-7) were missing two starting seniors and one starting junior in the Northern Illinois Big 12 East loss. 
“Our lack of size and experience really hurt us today,” Morris coach David Valdivia said.
